"""
mkt-original commentary: Ezekiel 1-5 (all missing verses; ch1 v28 already seeded)
Layer: original — Hebrew vocabulary, grammar, key terms, exegetical notes
Key Hebrew: ben adam (93×), yad YHWH, hayyot, ophanim, demut/mareh, hashmal,
  ben adam, tsopheh (watchman), nasa avon (bearing iniquity), tabur ha-aretz
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / f"mkt-{layer}" / f"{book}.json"
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / f"mkt-{layer}" / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ORIGINAL_1 = {
  "1": "<p>The opening date formula places Ezekiel in 593 BCE (the thirtieth year, probably Ezekiel's own age — the year a Levite was to begin priestly service, Num 4:3). The setting is the Chebar Canal in Babylonia, among the first exiles deported in 597 BCE. The phrase <strong>marot elohim</strong> (<em>marʾôt ʾĕlōhîm</em>) — 'visions of God' — signals that what follows is not ordinary prophetic speech but direct visual encounter with the divine; the plural <em>marʾôt</em> (visions) is the standard term for visionary experience in later Hebrew prophecy (cf. Dan 8:1; Zech 1:8).</p>",
  "2": "<p><strong>galut</strong> (<em>gālût</em>): 'captivity, exile.' The technical term for the exilic community — those carried away from the land. Ezekiel's call comes in the midst of the exile, not in the land; the divine glory is not confined to Zion but can be encountered at the Chebar River in Babylon. This is theologically radical: YHWH is present with the exiles, not merely with those who remain in the land. The Joiachin deportation (597 BCE) is the reference point — the fifth year of King Jehoiachin's exile.</p>",
  "3": "<p><strong>yad YHWH</strong> (<em>yad Yhwh</em>): 'the hand of YHWH.' The formula for prophetic compulsion — the overpowering divine energy that takes hold of the prophet (cf. 1 Kgs 18:46; Isa 8:11; Jer 15:17). In Ezekiel it appears with particular frequency (1:3; 3:14, 22; 8:1; 37:1; 40:1), marking each major visionary episode. The hand of YHWH functions as both a physical sensation and a metaphor for the divine initiative: Ezekiel does not choose to enter the vision — it seizes him. <strong>hayah</strong> (<em>hāyâ</em>) 'was/came upon' — the perfect tense in Hebrew here marks a completed decisive event.</p>",
  "4": "<p><strong>ruach searah</strong> (<em>rûaḥ sĕʿārâh</em>): 'stormy wind/whirlwind.' The theophany begins with cosmic storm — the same elemental context as Sinai (Exod 19:16-18) and the Job theophany (Job 38:1). <strong>anan gadol</strong> (<em>ʿānān gādōl</em>): 'great cloud' — divine cloud always signals the Shekinah presence (Exod 16:10; 1 Kgs 8:10-11). <strong>esh mitlaqaqhat</strong> (<em>ʾēš mitlaqqaḥat</em>): 'flashing/flickering fire' — the continuous participle suggests ongoing motion, not a single flash. <strong>hashmal</strong> (<em>ḥašmal</em>): one of the most discussed words in biblical Hebrew; the LXX renders it <em>ēlektron</em> (electrum, a gold-silver alloy) — a gleaming, luminous metal. The Mishnah restricts public teaching of this passage (m. Hagigah 2:1), reflecting the mystery surrounding Ezekiel's throne-vision.</p>",
  "5": "<p><strong>arba hayyot</strong> (<em>ʾarbaʿ ḥayyôt</em>): 'four living creatures.' <em>Hayyot</em> (plural of <em>ḥayyâ</em>, living creature) becomes in Ezekiel the term for the beings supporting the divine chariot-throne; they are identified as cherubim in chapter 10. In John's Apocalypse (Rev 4:6-8) the same four creatures appear surrounding the heavenly throne, picking up Ezekiel's vision directly. The number four represents the four directions — the divine throne encompasses the totality of spatial reality.</p>",
  "6": "<p>Each creature has four wings — two spread upward meeting above, two covering the body. The four-wing configuration differs from the seraphim of Isaiah 6 (six wings) but shares the function of covering and flight. The wings touching one another above forms the <em>kappōret</em>-like space of the divine presence, recalling the cherubim whose wings overshadowed the ark (Exod 25:20). Ezekiel's beings are thus mobile cherubim — the portable ark-throne of the God who travels to Babylon with his people.</p>",
  "7": "<p>The feet are described as <strong>regel yeshara</strong> (<em>regel yĕšārâ</em>): 'straight/single foot' — possibly hooves rather than articulated feet, gleaming like polished bronze (<strong>nechoshet qalal</strong>, <em>nĕḥōšet qālāl</em>). Bronze/copper is consistently the metal of divine judgment in Ezekiel and Daniel (Dan 10:6; Rev 1:15). The sparkling bronze feet that move without turning sideways represent the directional omnipresence of the divine will.</p>",
  "8": "<p>Human hands under their wings — <strong>yedot adam</strong> (<em>yĕdôt ʾādām</em>) — the creatures have both animal/celestial features and human hands, combining heavenly and earthly registers. The four-sided symmetry (hands on all four sides, faces on all four sides) means the divine chariot has no front or back — it operates equally in all directions simultaneously. This is a theological statement: divine action has no preferred direction, no blind spot.</p>",
  "9": "<p>Their wings touch one another — the connected wings create a unified covering over the expanse between them. When they move they go straight forward without turning (<strong>lo yisabu belekhtam</strong>, <em>lōʾ yissabbû bĕlektām</em>) — the Hebrew emphasizes directional constancy. The chariot-throne moves in any direction while the creatures themselves maintain their orientation; it is the wheels, not the creatures, that change direction. This engineering-like precision in the description reflects Ezekiel's priestly attention to exact sacred-space geometry.</p>",
  "10": "<p>The four faces — <strong>pene adam</strong> (<em>pĕnê ʾādām</em>): human face (front right); <strong>pene aryeh</strong> (<em>pĕnê ʾaryēh</em>): lion face (right); <strong>pene shor</strong> (<em>pĕnê šôr</em>): ox face (left); <strong>pene nesher</strong> (<em>pĕnê nešer</em>): eagle face (back). The four faces represent the four domains of living creatures (human, wild animal, domestic animal, bird) — the divine throne encompasses all creaturely modes of existence. Irenaeus (2nd century) identified these four faces with the four Gospels (human=Matthew, lion=John, ox=Luke, eagle=Mark — or in various orderings), a tradition that shaped medieval Christian iconography of the four evangelists.</p>",
  "11": "<p>Two wings spread upward and touched another's wings above; two wings covered the body. The spreading wings above form the <em>firmament</em> space (the expanse, <em>rāqîaʿ</em>, mentioned in v. 22-26) while the covering wings preserve modesty — the covering of the divine presence is always paired with disclosure (cf. the seraphim covering faces and feet in Isa 6:2). The creatures' posture enacts both revelation and hiddenness simultaneously.</p>",
  "12": "<p>Each creature goes straight forward — wherever the spirit goes, they go. <strong>ruach</strong> (<em>rûaḥ</em>) here means either 'spirit' (animating will) or 'wind' (direction) — the ambiguity is probably intentional. The creatures' motion is Spirit-directed: they do not move by their own initiative but by the ruach's leading. This pictures the total responsiveness of the divine chariot-mechanism to the divine will — no friction, no lag, no resistance.</p>",
  "13": "<p>Their appearance was like burning coals of fire (<strong>like the appearance of torches</strong>, <em>legaḥălê ʾēš</em>), flashing up and down among the creatures. Fire moving among the living beings connects to the divine fire that accompanies theophany throughout the OT (burning bush, pillar of fire, Sinai). The fire that 'moves back and forth' (<em>mithallek</em>) is the same participle used for God 'walking' in the garden (Gen 3:8) — the divine presence in perpetual active motion.</p>",
  "14": "<p>The creatures dart (<strong>ratsot</strong>, <em>rāṣôʾ</em>) and return (<strong>shov</strong>, <em>šôb</em>) like the appearance of a flash of lightning (<strong>bazaq</strong>, <em>bāzāq</em>). The darting-and-returning motion of lightning is the closest natural analogy for the otherworldly speed of the divine chariot-creatures. The darting and returning movement also evokes the rabbinic image of the <em>ma'ase merkabah</em> (chariot work) — the mystical contemplation of this passage that became foundational for Jewish mysticism.</p>",
  "15": "<p>As I looked at the living creatures, I saw a wheel on the earth beside each living creature — <strong>ophan</strong> (<em>ʾôp̄ān</em>): wheel. The four wheels beside the four creatures introduce the chariot's mobile infrastructure. <strong>arba panav</strong>: the four of them — each wheel has four faces (is equidirectional). The wheels are the interface between the heavenly chariot and the earthly surface, enabling movement in any direction.</p>",
  "16": "<p>The wheels' appearance: <strong>ke-ein tarshish</strong> (<em>kĕʿên taršîš</em>): 'like chrysolite/beryl' — a yellow-green gemstone (Tarshish stone; Dan 10:6 uses the same). The four wheels all have the same form. <strong>ophan betoch ophan</strong> (<em>ʾôp̄ān bĕtôk ʾôp̄ān</em>): 'wheel within a wheel' — the most discussed image of the vision. The concentric-wheel structure probably represents a gyroscope-like mechanism enabling movement in any direction without turning. This image became iconic in Jewish mysticism and has been widely noted as an analogy for complex mechanical systems.</p>",
  "17": "<p>When they moved they went in any of the four directions without turning (<strong>lo yisabu belekhtam</strong>): the directional freedom of the wheel-within-wheel system. Four-directional omnidirectional movement without pivoting is mechanically impossible for ordinary wheels — the vision describes a supernatural mobility system. The theological point: God's governance of history moves in any direction simultaneously without the limitations of fixed orientation.</p>",
  "18": "<p><strong>gavoah</strong> (<em>gābōah</em>): 'height/loftiness.' The rims of the four wheels were tall and awesome (<strong>yira</strong>, <em>yîrāʾ</em>, inspiring fear). The rims were full of eyes (<strong>einayim</strong>, <em>ʿênayim</em>) all around the four of them. Eyes on the rims: the divine chariot's wheels are all-seeing; every movement is watched in all directions simultaneously. In Rev 4:6 the four living creatures are 'full of eyes all around and within,' combining the eyes of the chariot creatures and the eyes of Ezekiel's wheels.</p>",
  "19": "<p>When the living creatures moved, the wheels moved beside them; when the creatures rose from the earth, the wheels also rose. The total synchrony between living creatures and wheels: the organic beings and the mechanical system move as one unified entity. This synchrony will become the basis for the visionary language of divine-human integration in Ezekiel — the prophet's movements are eventually synchronized with divine instruction in the same way.</p>",
  "20": "<p>Wherever the ruach wished to go, they went — wherever the ruach went, the wheels went with them, for the ruach of the living creatures was in the wheels. <strong>ruach hahayyah beopanim</strong> (<em>rûaḥ haḥayyâ bāʾôp̄annîm</em>): 'the ruach of the living creature in the wheels.' The animating ruach pervades both the organic creatures and the mechanical wheels — there is no division between the spiritual and the material in the divine chariot. This anticipates Ezekiel's pneumatology: the ruach that animates the chariot is the same ruach that will animate the valley of dry bones (37:9-14).</p>",
  "21": "<p>When they rose, the wheels rose; when they stopped, the wheels stopped; when they lifted themselves from the earth, the wheels lifted alongside them. The triple correspondence seals the synchrony described in vv. 19-20. The repetition of the pattern is characteristic of Ezekiel's priestly precision — like the tabernacle instructions of Exodus that repeat specifications in both command and execution forms, Ezekiel repeats the chariot's movement principles to establish their reliability as observable law.</p>",
  "22": "<p><strong>raqia</strong> (<em>rāqîaʿ</em>): 'expanse/firmament.' The same word used for the sky-dome of Gen 1:6-8. <strong>qerach hanora</strong> (<em>qeraḥ hannôrāʾ</em>): 'awesome crystal/ice' — <em>qeraḥ</em> means frost or ice; the radiant crystal platform stretched over the heads of the living creatures like the icy brightness of the sky. The expanse is simultaneously the floor of the divine throne-platform and the ceiling of the creaturely domain — marking the boundary between the earthly and heavenly realms. The awesome (<em>nôrāʾ</em>) quality emphasizes that this boundary inspires reverent fear.</p>",
  "23": "<p>Under the expanse the wings of the living creatures stretched toward one another; each creature had two wings covering its body. The structural arrangement is now clarified: wings spread upward touching above the expanse; wings downward covering the body below. The upward-spreading wings that touch above the crystal expanse form the supporting structure for the divine throne; the body-covering wings maintain the creatures' modesty before the divine holiness seated above them.</p>",
  "24": "<p>The sound of their wings was like the roar of mighty waters (<strong>qol mayim rabim</strong>, <em>qôl mayim rabbîm</em>), like the voice of the Almighty (<strong>qol Shaddai</strong>, <em>qôl Šadday</em>), like the sound of an army camp. The triple simile for the sound: (1) the cosmic ocean (waters above; Gen 1:7), (2) El Shaddai's own voice, and (3) a military host. <em>Shaddai</em> as the divine name connects to the patriarchal traditions (Gen 17:1; 28:3); its use here alongside the more characteristic Ezekielian <em>Adonai YHWH</em> gives the sound an archaic patriarchal resonance. John's vision of the living creatures in Rev 4:8 picks up the thunderous sound tradition.</p>",
  "25": "<p>When they stood still, they lowered their wings — the sound ceases when motion ceases. The dynamic responsiveness of the chariot (sound when moving, silence when stopped) mirrors the pattern of divine communication in Ezekiel: when the hand of YHWH is active, the prophet speaks; when the hand withdraws, the prophet is silent (3:25-27). There was a voice above the expanse (<strong>qol mimal laragia</strong>) — the threshold between movement-noise and divine speech is the expanse that marks the creaturely-heavenly boundary.</p>",
  "26": "<p><strong>even sapir</strong> (<em>ʾeben sappîr</em>): 'sapphire-like stone.' The lapis lazuli (the actual identification of biblical <em>sappîr</em>) forms the appearance of the throne. The sapphire throne appears in Moses's vision (Exod 24:10: 'under his feet was something like a pavement made of lapis lazuli, clear as the sky') — Ezekiel's vision is a more elaborate and personal encounter with the same throne-reality. <strong>demut kisse</strong> (<em>dĕmût kissēʾ</em>): 'likeness of a throne' — Ezekiel uses <em>demut</em> (likeness) and <em>mareh</em> (appearance) throughout to maintain appropriate distance from unqualified assertion: he sees the likeness of the throne, not the throne itself. <strong>demut kemarat adam</strong>: 'likeness like the appearance of a human' — the enthroned form above the sapphire throne looks human. The anthropomorphic divine form will become central to Jewish mysticism (<em>Shiur Qomah</em> literature) and Christian incarnation theology.</p>",
  "27": "<p><strong>hashmal</strong> (<em>ḥašmal</em>) again — from his loins upward, and again downward, surrounded by fire. The bipartite division of the enthroned figure — gleaming metal above, fire below — corresponds to fire both as judgment and as holiness. The brightness (<strong>nogah</strong>, <em>nōgah</em>) all around: the same word used in v. 4 for the brightness surrounding the initial theophanic cloud. The full circle of light that surrounds the enthroned figure is the divine <em>kavod</em> radiating outward — the glory both conceals and reveals the divine person."
}

ORIGINAL_2 = {
  "1": "<p><strong>ben adam</strong> (<em>ben ʾādām</em>): 'son of man / son of Adam.' The most characteristic divine address to Ezekiel, used 93 times in the book (more than any other OT book). <em>Ben ʾādām</em> means simply 'human being' — it is the term that marks Ezekiel's creatureliness before the divine presence. The contrast is deliberate: the divine being enthroned in chapter 1 has the <em>demut kemarat adam</em> (likeness like a human) while the prophet is addressed as <em>ben ʾādām</em> (a human being) — the human below and the anthropomorphic divine above, both using the vocabulary of human form. In Daniel 7:13 the phrase becomes a messianic title ('one like a son of man'); in the NT, Jesus's consistent self-designation 'the Son of Man' draws on both traditions.</p>",
  "2": "<p><strong>ruach baah vi</strong> (<em>rûaḥ bāʾâ bî</em>): 'the Spirit came into me.' The Spirit that animates the chariot-wheels (1:20-21) is the same Spirit that now enters the prophet. The entry of the ruach into Ezekiel is the link between the visionary encounter and the prophetic commission: he cannot stand without the Spirit entering him (cf. 3:24). The divine voice speaks first, then the Spirit enters to enable response — the order of grace: word, then enablement to hear it.</p>",
  "3": "<p>Sent to the children of Israel, to the rebellious nations (<strong>goyim hamordim</strong>, <em>gôyîm hāmōrĕdîm</em>). The term <strong>marad</strong> (<em>mārad</em>) — to rebel — is stronger than the more common <em>pāšaʿ</em> (transgress); it carries the connotation of open political revolt against a sovereign. Israel is addressed as <em>goyim</em> (nations/Gentiles) — a shocking term, usually reserved for foreign peoples. Their rebellion has characterized them 'to this day' (<em>ʿad hayyôm hazzeh</em>): persistent, ongoing, unreformed. The fathers rebelled and the sons have not stopped.</p>",
  "4": "<p>Israel is <strong>azei panim</strong> (<em>ʿazzê p̄ānîm</em>): 'hard of face/impudent' and <strong>hazaq lev</strong> (<em>ḥĕzaq lēb</em>): 'hardened of heart.' The two body-part metaphors describe spiritual resistance: the face (what one presents to others) is hard/impudent — unashamed, uncowed; the heart (decision-making center) is hardened against the word. Paul's description of the unregenerate heart in Romans 1:21 (their foolish hearts were darkened) and the hardening of Israel in Rom 11:7 both draw on this OT vocabulary of <em>ḥĕzaq lēb</em>.</p>",
  "5": "<p>'Whether they listen or not' (<strong>yishmehu veIM yichdalu</strong>, <em>yišmĕʿû wĕʾim yeḥdālû</em>): the prophetic mission is not conditioned on success. The prophet is called to speak the divine word regardless of reception — a theme that will be intensified in ch. 3. This is the hermeneutic key to Ezekiel's entire ministry: the word goes forth whether it is received or rejected; the prophet's faithfulness is the only variable under his control. <strong>ki beit meri hemah</strong> (<em>kî bêt mĕrî hēmmâ</em>): 'for they are a house of rebellion' — the label <em>beit meri</em> (house of rebellion) recurs throughout Ezekiel as the characteristic designation of his audience.</p>",
  "6": "<p>'Do not be afraid of them, do not be afraid of their words' — even when briers and thorns are around you and you sit on scorpions. The three images of the hostile audience: <strong>saravim</strong> (<em>sārābbîm</em>, thorns/briers), <strong>qotsim</strong> (<em>qôṣîm</em>, thorns/spines), <strong>aqravim</strong> (<em>ʿaqrabbîm</em>, scorpions). The scorpion image is particularly striking: not just passive thorns but actively dangerous creatures. The prophet is called to sit among them without flinching — divine fearlessness as the mark of genuine prophetic calling (cf. Jer 1:17; 1 Kgs 18:15).</p>",
  "7": "<p>Whether they listen or refuse — they are a rebellious house (<em>beit meri</em>). The repetition from v. 5 forms a frame around vv. 5-7: the commission is unchanged by the audience's likely rejection. The Hebrew perfect <strong>yishmehu</strong> (they will listen) and imperfect <strong>yichdalu</strong> (they will refuse) are both uncertain futures — the prophet cannot know which will occur. But the commission stands either way.</p>",
  "8": "<p>'But you, son of man, hear what I say to you — do not be rebellious like that rebellious house; open your mouth and eat what I give you.' The contrast between Ezekiel and Israel: Israel is the <em>beit meri</em>; Ezekiel must be the opposite. The command <strong>lo tehieh meri</strong> (<em>lōʾ tihyê mĕrî</em>): 'do not be a rebel' — explicitly applying the label they bear to the possible failure mode of the prophet himself. The prophet is not immune to the temptation of rebellion; the command is necessary because the commission is costly.</p>",
  "9": "<p>A hand was stretched out to me, and in it was a scroll (<strong>meghillat sefer</strong>, <em>mĕgillat sēp̄er</em>). <em>Meghillah</em> is a rolled scroll (from <em>gālal</em>, to roll). The scroll is stretched toward Ezekiel by a hand — presumably the hand of the enthroned figure of chapter 1 (whose hand of judgment/commission recurs throughout). The scroll contains the divine message that Ezekiel must internalize before proclamation.</p>",
  "10": "<p>Written on its front and back — <strong>panim veahor</strong> (<em>pānîm wĕʾāḥôr</em>): front and back, both sides. The contents: <strong>qinot vehageh vehi</strong> (<em>qinôt wahegeh wāhî</em>): 'lamentations and mourning and woe.' Three words for grief, all expressing the negative content of Ezekiel's prophetic message. The double-sided writing means the message is completely full — there is no space for anything else. The divine word to Judah is entirely lament. John's little scroll in Rev 10:8-10 is the same <em>meghillah</em> tradition: the scroll eaten by the prophet contains judgment that is sweet to receive but bitter in effect.</p>"
}

ORIGINAL_3 = {
  "1": "<p>The command to eat the scroll is repeated — the double command (2:8 and 3:1) emphasizes the necessity of internalization before proclamation. <strong>melet bitnek</strong> (<em>millēʾ biṭnĕkā</em>): 'fill your stomach/belly with it.' The belly (<em>beten</em>) — the interior of the person — must receive the scroll completely before the mouth can speak. The bodily metaphor is deliberate: the word of God must become part of the prophet's physical existence, not merely an external message he relays. Cf. Jeremiah's word as 'fire shut up in my bones' (Jer 20:9).</p>",
  "2": "<p>Ezekiel opens his mouth and the divine hand feeds him the scroll. The passive construction — 'he gave me the scroll to eat' — maintains the divine initiative: Ezekiel does not choose to eat, he is fed. The word of God is not self-generated by the prophet but received and then re-expressed. This is the model for all biblical inspiration: the human vessel receives what comes from outside.</p>",
  "3": "<p>In my mouth it was like honey (<strong>devash</strong>, <em>dĕḇaš</em>) for sweetness. The sweetness of the scroll is a genuine and full sweetness, not ironic — the word of God is intrinsically delightful even when its content is judgment (cf. Ps 19:10: 'sweeter than honey and drippings of the honeycomb'; Ps 119:103). The prophet who tastes the sweetness of the word can proclaim judgment without bitterness — the tragedy of the message is held within the sweetness of being entrusted with it.</p>",
  "4": "<p>'Go to the house of Israel and speak my words to them' — the commission restated after the scroll-eating. The message that Ezekiel was caused to eat is the same message he must now deliver: there is no gap between the received word and the proclaimed word. The digested scroll becomes the prophetic speech. This is the ideal of prophetic integrity: the prophet speaks not his own thoughts about God but the very words he has internalized.</p>",
  "5": "<p>'You are not being sent to a people of foreign speech (<strong>shefat am</strong>, <em>śĕp̄at ʿam</em>) and difficult language (<strong>lishan kaved</strong>, <em>lāšôn kābēd</em>).' The 'heavy tongue' (literally 'heavy language') is the same idiom Moses used for his own speech impediment (Exod 4:10: <em>kĕbad peh</em>, heavy of mouth). Ezekiel is not sent to those whose language he cannot understand — his commission is specifically to his own people who share his language but refuse to understand.</p>",
  "6": "<p>'If I had sent you to foreign peoples of unfamiliar speech and difficult language, they would have listened to you.' The shocking comparison: pagan foreigners would have been more receptive to the divine word than covenant Israel. This is the same pattern Jesus invokes (Matt 11:21-24: Tyre and Sidon would have repented) and Paul develops (Rom 1:18-32; the Gentiles who have the law written on their hearts). The accessibility of the word to outsiders heightens the culpability of insiders who resist it.</p>",
  "7": "<p>'But the house of Israel will not listen to you because they will not listen to me — for all the house of Israel is <strong>hazak-metsach</strong> (<em>ḥĕzaq-mēṣaḥ</em>): hard of forehead (impudent/brazen) and <strong>qesheh-lev</strong> (<em>qĕšê-lēb</em>): stubborn of heart.' Two anatomical metaphors: forehead (public face of stubborn refusal to bow) and heart (inner decision-making center). The double hardness means they are resistant both externally (will not appear to yield) and internally (do not want to yield). The compound picture is of complete spiritual calcification.</p>",
  "8": "<p>'But I have made your face as hard as their faces, and your forehead as hard as their foreheads.' The divine response to Israel's brazen resistance: God hardens the prophet's face to match — not in stubbornness of sin but in unflinching proclamation. <strong>natatih paneika chazaq linegev penehem</strong> (<em>nātattî p̄ānêkā ḥāzāq lĕneged p̄ĕnêhem</em>): 'I have made your face strong against their face.' The prophet's prophetic courage is not natural human bravery but God-given resistance to human intimidation.</p>",
  "9": "<p><strong>shamir</strong> (<em>šāmîr</em>): 'adamant/emery' — the hardest stone known in antiquity, used to cut other stones. Your forehead like adamant, harder than flint (<strong>challamish</strong>, <em>ḥallāmîš</em>). The escalation: adamant harder than flint. The prophet who must stand against the stony resistance of Israel is given a forehead of harder stone — divine hardness against human hardness. 'Do not be afraid of them and do not be dismayed at their looks, for they are a rebellious house.'</p>",
  "10": "<p>'Son of man, take all my words into your heart (<strong>levaveka</strong>, <em>lĕbābĕkā</em>) and hear with your ears.' The double command — heart first, then ears — reverses the ordinary sequence (ears hear, then heart receives). The divine word requires not just auditory reception but internalization: the prophet who will proclaim must first have the word lodge in his heart-center. This is the basis for the new covenant promise of Jer 31:33 (law written on hearts) which Ezekiel parallels in 36:26-27.</p>",
  "11": "<p>'Go to your own people, to the exiles, and speak to them. Say to them, &#8220;Thus says the Lord GOD&#8221; — whether they listen or they refuse (<strong>yishmehu veIM yichdalu</strong>).' The phrase 'whether they listen or not' recurs (2:5, 7; 3:11) as the theological framework for prophetic ministry independent of results. Ezekiel is sent first to the exiles — those already in Babylon — before the fall of Jerusalem (in 586 BCE). His ministry is among the community that sees themselves as abandoned by God, teaching them to find the divine presence even in exile.</p>",
  "12": "<p>The Spirit lifted me up (<strong>vatisani ruach</strong>, <em>wattissāʾēnî rûaḥ</em>), and behind me I heard a great rumbling (<strong>qol raash gadol</strong>, <em>qôl raʿaš gādôl</em>): 'Blessed be the glory of YHWH from his place' (<strong>baruch kevod YHWH mimqomo</strong>). The doxology is the response of the chariot-beings to the divine departure — the chariot moves when the Spirit lifts the prophet. <em>Baruch kevod YHWH</em> is a formal liturgical doxology; <em>mimqomo</em> (from his place) — an unusual phrase that may mean 'wherever he is,' reflecting the new theology of the mobile divine presence that is not confined to Zion.</p>",
  "13": "<p>The sound of the living creatures' wings touching one another, and the sound of the wheels beside them — the full auditory impact of the departing chariot, described as a great roar. The prophet experiences the sound of the divine departure even as he is being sent on mission. The departure of the chariot from the Chebar to commission a prophetic mission is itself a theological statement: the divine glory moves to empower the prophet who moves toward the exiles.</p>",
  "14": "<p><strong>vaelech mar uvachamat ruach</strong> (<em>wāʾēlēk mār ûvaḥămat rûaḥ</em>): 'I went in bitterness (<em>mār</em>) and in the heat/rage of the Spirit (<em>ḥămat rûaḥ</em>).' The prophet's emotional state: bitter, hot with prophetic compulsion. <em>Mār</em> (bitter) is not spiritual bitterness or resentment but the visceral pain of one tasked with proclaiming judgment to his own people. <strong>yad YHWH alai hazqa</strong> (<em>yad Yhwh ʿālay ḥāzĕqâ</em>): 'the hand of YHWH was strong upon me' — the divine compulsion that overcomes the prophet's personal grief and sets him in motion.</p>",
  "15": "<p>Arrived at Tel-abib (<strong>tel aviv</strong>, <em>tel ʾābîb</em>): 'mound of the spring flood' (probably from Akkadian <em>tēl abubi</em>, mound of the great flood — a tell raised by the primeval flood-disaster; later the name of the first Hebrew city in modern Israel). The prophet sits with the exiles and remains among them overwhelmed (<strong>mashim</strong>, <em>maštîm</em> or <em>mĕšōmēm</em>) for seven days. The seven-day stunned silence before speaking parallels the seven-day mourning/ordination period (Lev 8:33) — the prophet undergoes a kind of ordination through communal sitting before he speaks.</p>",
  "16": "<p>At the end of seven days, the word of YHWH came to Ezekiel — the prophetic reception formula that will introduce the new commission of watchman. The seven-day waiting period is ended not by the prophet's initiative but by the word's arrival: divine speech determines the timing of prophecy, not the prophet's readiness. This is consistent with Ezekiel's overall pattern of passive reception followed by active proclamation.</p>",
  "17": "<p><strong>tsopheh</strong> (<em>ṣōp̄eh</em>): 'watchman.' The specific term for the sentinel stationed on the city wall to watch for approaching threats. Ezekiel is appointed as a watchman (<em>nātattîkā ṣōp̄eh</em>: I have appointed you a watchman) for the house of Israel. The watchman metaphor defines his role: not priest (though he is one), not king, not intercessor, but a sentinel responsible for warning. The watchman analogy establishes the life-or-death stakes of prophetic proclamation: failure to warn means complicity in the death of the warned.</p>",
  "18": "<p>'If I say to the wicked, &#8220;You will certainly die,&#8221; and you give no warning — that wicked person will die for his iniquity, but I will require his blood from your hand.' <strong>damim</strong> (<em>dāmîm</em>): 'blood (guilt)' — the plural of <em>dām</em> used for bloodguilt, legal responsibility for death (Num 35:27; 2 Sam 16:8). The prophet who fails to warn is held legally responsible for the spiritual blood of the unwarned. Paul uses this exact framework in Acts 20:26: 'I am innocent of the blood of all of you, for I did not shrink from declaring the whole counsel of God' — Paul fulfills the watchman obligation of Ezek 3:18.</p>",
  "19": "<p>'But if you warn the wicked and he does not turn from his wickedness — he will die in his iniquity, but you will have saved your life (<strong>nafshecha hitsalta</strong>, <em>nap̄šĕkā hiṣṣaltā</em>).' The watchman's faithfulness determines his own fate, not the wicked's choice. The double outcome: the unrepentant wicked person dies, but the faithful warner lives. This is the covenantal principle of individual moral responsibility — each person bears their own iniquity, but the prophet who fails to warn bears theirs alongside his own.</p>",
  "20": "<p>'And when a righteous person turns from their righteousness and commits iniquity, and I place a stumbling block before them, they will die.' <strong>mikhshol</strong> (<em>mikšôl</em>): 'stumbling block' — YHWH placing a stumbling block before the would-be sinner who turns from righteousness is a concept that has generated theological debate (divine permission vs. divine causation of sin). The context in Ezekiel emphasizes individual responsibility: the turning from righteousness is the sinner's own act; the stumbling block is the consequence, not the cause. Paul uses <em>proskomma</em> (stumbling block) in Rom 14:13 and 1 Cor 8:9 in the related context of causing others to fall.</p>",
  "21": "<p>'If you warn the righteous not to sin, and they take warning and do not sin, they will surely live because they took warning — and you will have saved your life.' The fourfold case structure (wicked/unwarned, wicked/warned, righteous-who-falls/unwarned, righteous/warned) establishes the comprehensive scope of the watchman's responsibility. The final case — the righteous who is warned and remains righteous — is the positive conclusion: the ministry of warning can preserve righteousness as well as call back the wicked.</p>",
  "22": "<p><strong>yad YHWH</strong> (<em>yad Yhwh</em>) again — the third occurrence in the book (1:3; 3:14; 3:22), marking the beginning of the next visionary episode. The divine hand comes upon Ezekiel in the valley (<strong>biq'ah</strong>, <em>biqʿâ</em>) — the same Hebrew word used for the Valley of Dry Bones in ch. 37. The valley is the place of open divine encounter outside the city, outside the temple precincts — reinforcing the theme of mobile divine presence.</p>",
  "23": "<p>The glory of YHWH was there (<strong>kevod YHWH</strong>) — just like the vision at the Chebar (ch. 1). The second appearance of the divine chariot-glory confirms the identity of the Chebar vision and establishes continuity: Ezekiel has not been abandoned between the initial call-vision and this commission to silence and confinement. He falls on his face as before (1:28) — the prostration of the finite creature before infinite holiness.</p>",
  "24": "<p>The Spirit entered into him (<strong>vatavoh bi ruach</strong>) and set him on his feet — as in 2:2, the Spirit must enable standing before the word can be received. 'Go, shut yourself inside your house.' The divine command to confinement: after seven days of communal sitting among the exiles, now a period of isolation. The stages of Ezekiel's ministry: vision → commission → communal sitting → isolation → sign-acts. Each stage is divinely ordered.</p>",
  "25": "<p>'Cords will be put on you and you will be tied with them so you cannot go out among the people.' The physical confinement of the prophet — he will be bound by the community he was meant to serve. Whether literal or figurative (the social pressure of a hostile community keeping him confined), the bound prophet is the sign of a bound nation: Israel is in exile (the bonds of <em>galut</em>), and Ezekiel's immobility enacts the nation's captivity.</p>",
  "26": "<p>'I will make your tongue stick to the roof of your mouth — you will be silent (<strong>ne'elem</strong>, <em>neʾĕlam</em>) and unable to rebuke them.' The divine-imposed dumbness (<em>illem</em>) will be Ezekiel's condition until Jerusalem falls (33:22: 'my mouth was opened and I was no longer silent'). The dumbness is not total — Ezekiel speaks throughout (his oracles continue) — but he cannot speak freely for himself or as an intercessor (<em>tokiah</em>, rebuke/argue their case). His dumbness is the sign that the divine case against Israel is closed to human appeal.</p>",
  "27": "<p>'But whenever I speak to you, I will open your mouth, and you will say to them, &#8220;Thus says the Lord GOD.&#8221; Whoever listens, let him listen; and whoever refuses, let him refuse — for they are a rebellious house.' The final restatement: the prophetic word depends entirely on divine initiative ('when I speak to you, I will open your mouth') and is entirely unconditioned by audience response ('whoever listens, let him; whoever refuses, let him'). The watchman has delivered the warning; the outcome belongs to those who hear."
}

ORIGINAL_4 = {
  "1": "<p><strong>levena</strong> (<em>lĕbēnâ</em>): 'brick/tile' — unbaked clay tablets were the writing material of Mesopotamia (cuneiform tablets); here Ezekiel inscribes (<strong>chuqita</strong>, <em>ḥuqîtā</em>) Jerusalem onto the clay, turning the Babylonian medium of record-keeping into the visual surface for Israel's judgment. The sign-act (<em>ôt</em>) transforms the prophet's body and surroundings into a prophetic performance — enacted oracle rather than spoken oracle. The use of a clay tile is culturally resonant: Babylon conquered by its own medium.</p>",
  "2": "<p>The siege works: <strong>dayeq</strong> (<em>dāyeq</em>, siege wall), <strong>solelah</strong> (<em>sōlĕlâ</em>, ramp/embankment), <strong>machanot</strong> (<em>maḥănôt</em>, encampments), <strong>karim</strong> (<em>kārîm</em>, battering rams). All four elements of ancient siege warfare arrayed against the clay Jerusalem. The enumeration is technical — Ezekiel has seen siege warfare in his lifetime and describes the full complement of ancient military siege engineering. The sign-act forces the exiles to watch their city being besieged in miniature, months before the historical siege will be complete.</p>",
  "3": "<p><strong>machavat barzel</strong> (<em>maḥăbat barzel</em>): 'iron griddle/pan' — placed as an iron wall (<strong>qir barzel</strong>, <em>qîr barzel</em>) between Ezekiel and the clay city. The iron wall between prophet and Jerusalem represents the divine separation — YHWH has erected an iron barrier between himself and the city, shutting off the normal channels of prophetic intercession. The sign concludes: <strong>zeh ot</strong> (<em>zeh ʾôt</em>), 'this is a sign to the house of Israel.' The sign is not merely illustrative but constitutive — it participates in the reality it depicts.</p>",
  "4": "<p><strong>nasa avon</strong> (<em>nāśāʾ ʿāwôn</em>): 'to bear/lift up iniquity.' This is one of the most important theological terms in the OT — the verb <em>nāśāʾ</em> (to carry, lift, bear) with its object <em>ʿāwôn</em> (iniquity, guilt, punishment). Ezekiel lying on his side bearing Israel's iniquity is a prophetic sign-act of substitutionary bearing: the prophet physically enacts the weight of covenant guilt through his constrained body. The same verbal combination (<em>nāśāʾ ʿāwôn</em>) appears in Isa 53:11-12 (the Servant bears the iniquity of many) and Num 14:34 (you shall bear your iniquity forty years). The 390-day performance is the physical vocabulary of covenant guilt-bearing.</p>",
  "5": "<p>Three hundred and ninety days (<strong>shalosh maot vetishim yom</strong>) = the years of Israel's iniquity. The number 390 has been variously calculated: as the sum of years from the division of the kingdom (931 BCE) to the end of exile; as the period from the Exodus to the temple dedication minus the 40 wilderness years; or as a typological number rather than a precise historical calculation. The key theological move is the day-for-year principle (<strong>yom lashanah yom lashanah</strong>, <em>yôm lāšānâ</em>): Ezekiel's physical ordeal compresses centuries of covenant history into months of bodily suffering.</p>",
  "6": "<p>Forty days for Judah's iniquity — a day for each year. The 40-year connection to the wilderness wandering (Num 14:34 explicitly uses the same day-for-year equation) casts the Babylonian exile as a second wilderness: a period of purging and preparation for a second entry into the land. The temporal symbolism is not precise chronology but covenantal typology.</p>",
  "7": "<p>'Turn your face toward the besieged Jerusalem with your arm bared' — <strong>zeroa chasufah</strong> (<em>zĕrôaʿ ḥăśûp̄â</em>): 'bared arm,' the idiom for divine power in action (Isa 52:10: YHWH bares his holy arm before all the nations; 53:1: to whom has the arm of YHWH been revealed?). The prophet's bared arm facing the clay Jerusalem embodies YHWH's own bared-arm judgment, being executed through the Babylonian siege. The prophet's body is the divine action made visible.</p>",
  "8": "<p>'I will put cords on you so that you cannot turn from side to side until you have completed the days of your siege.' The immobilization that was announced in 3:25 is now specified as part of the sign-act: the physical constraint on Ezekiel's body enacts the constraint of the siege on Jerusalem. The immobility is simultaneously the prophet's sign-act and his personal bearing of the city's judgment.</p>",
  "9": "<p>The mixed-grain bread: <strong>chita useorah uful ve'adashim udochan vekhussemeth</strong> — wheat, barley, beans, lentils, millet, and emmer wheat. This is siege-ration food — the mixture of available grains that a population under siege would bake when normal supplies were exhausted. The bread of distress (cf. Isa 30:20 'bread of distress and water of affliction') is the physical diet of the sign-act period, connecting the prophet's 390-day bodily experience to the lived experience of a besieged city.</p>",
  "10": "<p>Twenty shekels of food per day (<strong>esrim shekel</strong>, <em>ʿeśrîm šeqel</em>) — approximately 8 oz. / 225 grams, a starvation ration. The measured weight and set intervals (<strong>meit ad eit tochalennu</strong>, <em>mēʿēt ʿad ʿēt tôʾkĕlennû</em>) impose the discipline of famine proportioning on the prophet. The careful measurement dramatizes the systematic exhaustion of food supplies in a siege.</p>",
  "11": "<p>Water rationed at one-sixth of a hin (<em>šiššît hahîn</em>) — approximately 0.5 liters per day, severely inadequate for normal functioning. The combined food and water rations picture total deprivation: a person on these quantities would be visibly weakening, which is the visible sign. The prophet's deteriorating body is the living prophecy of Jerusalem's deterioration under siege.</p>",
  "12": "<p>Baked over <strong>gallelei tseat ha-adam</strong> (<em>gĕlālê ṣēʾat hāʾādām</em>): 'discs of human excrement.' The ultimate ritual defilement for a priest: cooking over human waste. The orderly, detail-oriented priest who has spent his life maintaining purity distinctions is commanded to violate the deepest levels of priestly cleanness. This enacts the defilement of the exile itself — Israel driven among the nations will eat defiled (<em>tameh</em>) bread, unable to maintain ritual purity in diaspora conditions.</p>",
  "13": "<p>'This is how the Israelites will eat their defiled bread among the nations to which I will scatter them.' The sign-act explains its own meaning: the prophet's defilement in the sign = the nation's defilement in exile. The verb <strong>adam</strong> (<em>ʾādām</em>) in context: <em>ṭāmēʾ</em> (defiled/unclean) is the technical priestly term (Lev 11:43) — what Ezekiel enacts in the sign, the exiles will live in the nations where maintaining ritual purity is impossible.</p>",
  "14": "<p>Ezekiel protests (<strong>achah Adonai YHWH</strong>, <em>ʾăhāh ʾădōnāy Yhwh</em>): 'Ah, Lord GOD!' — the formula of prophetic protest (Jer 1:6; 4:10; 14:13). His protest centers on his priestly cleanness: from youth to the present (<em>mineuray ve'ad atah</em>) he has never eaten what died naturally or was mauled — never eaten <strong>nevelah</strong> (carrion) or <strong>terefa</strong> (torn flesh), both prohibited in Lev 11 and 17. The protest is not disobedience but priestly integrity — the covenant-keeper for whom defilement is not just distasteful but self-defining.</p>",
  "15": "<p>Divine concession: cattle dung (<strong>tsapat habaqar</strong>, <em>ṣĕpieʿ habbāqār</em>) instead of human dung. The divine accommodation to the prophet's priestly integrity allows a less ritually defiling fuel (cattle dung was commonly used as fuel in the ancient Near East). The concession does not annul the sign but modifies its medium — the defilement is still present (impure fuel for a priest) but not at the maximum level. God's responsiveness to the prophet's conscientious objection is itself a theological datum.</p>",
  "16": "<p>'I will break the staff of bread (<strong>mateh lechem</strong>, <em>maṭṭēh leḥem</em>) in Jerusalem.' The staff of bread — bread as the support/staff that sustains life (Lev 26:26; Ps 105:16; Isa 3:1) — will be broken: the food supply will be cut off. The inhabitants will eat their rationed bread with dread (<strong>deagah</strong>, <em>dĕʾāgâ</em>) and drink their measured water in horror (<strong>shamemah</strong>, <em>šāmĕmâ</em>). The emotional states (dread, horror) as well as the physical deprivation will mark the siege-life of Jerusalem.</p>",
  "17": "<p>'They will lack bread and water, look at each other in horror (<strong>nashammu ish veachiv</strong>, <em>nāšammû ʾîš wĕʾāḥîw</em>: they will be desolate, each man with his brother), and waste away (<strong>nemaqu</strong>, <em>nāmaqû</em>) because of their iniquity.' The final outcome: communal horror and individual wasting. <em>Māqaq</em> (to rot, waste away) is used for physical decay — the iniquity that caused the siege now causes the physical deterioration of the besieged. The connection between moral state and physical condition is explicit: they waste away because of their iniquity, not merely because of food shortage."
}

ORIGINAL_5 = {
  "1": "<p><strong>taar</strong> (<em>taʿar</em>): 'razor/sharp sword.' The command to use a sword as a barber's razor over head and beard is a multi-layered sign: (1) shaving the head and beard was a sign of extreme mourning and humiliation in the ancient Near East (Isa 15:2; 22:12; Jer 47:5); (2) the barber's razor over a prophet's head enacts the divine judgment 'cutting off' the people (cf. Isa 7:20: YHWH will shave with a hired razor — the king of Assyria — the head and the legs and the beard); (3) <strong>charba</strong> (<em>ḥarbâ</em>, sword) used as a razor: judgment-instrument as grooming-instrument. The scales (<strong>moznaim</strong>, <em>mōznayim</em>) to divide the hair into equal thirds introduces the tripartite judgment.</p>",
  "2": "<p>The three thirds: burn a third in fire in the middle of the city (when the siege days are complete); take a third and cut with the sword around it; scatter a third to the wind. The tripartite judgment pattern — fire (plague/famine death within the city), sword (those killed in the siege/battles), and scatter-to-wind (exile) — is the comprehensive instrument of covenant judgment (Lev 26:25, 33). The sword as a second pursuit after the scattered third: even in exile the judgment follows. The thirds structure becomes Ezekiel's characteristic judgment formula (5:12; 6:12).</p>",
  "3": "<p>A small number of hairs tucked into the fold of the cloak (<strong>kenafecha</strong>, <em>kĕnāp̄êkā</em>: 'your skirts/wings'). The remnant theme: a small quantity preserved within the judgment. <em>Kānāp̄</em> (wing/skirt/corner) is the same word used for Boaz spreading his wing/cloak over Ruth (Ruth 3:9) — the covering of divine protection. The remnant tucked in the cloak is the protected minority, the preserved seed within the judgment.</p>",
  "4": "<p>'Take some of those very hairs and throw them into the fire to burn; from that fire a flame will spread to all the house of Israel.' Even the preserved remnant does not escape entirely — some are thrown back into the fire, and from the burning remnant the judgment spreads to all Israel. This is the most severe element of the sign: no fully safe remnant. The flame spreading from the remnant's burning to 'all the house of Israel' anticipates the post-586 judgments that will affect even those not directly caught in the Jerusalem siege.</p>",
  "5": "<p><strong>tabur ha-aretz</strong> (<em>ṭabbûr hāʾāreṣ</em>): 'navel/center of the earth.' <em>Ṭabbûr</em> literally means 'navel' (also used for the highest point of a mountain, Judg 9:37). Jerusalem placed in the center (navel) of the nations expresses both the divine intention for Jerusalem as the hub of the nations' instruction (Isa 2:2-4; Mic 4:1-3) and the special culpability that follows from privilege: the city placed at the center of divine dealings with the world has the greatest responsibility and therefore the greatest accountability for failure.</p>",
  "6": "<p>'But she has rebelled against my laws more than the nations, and defied my statutes more than the surrounding countries.' The comparative: Jerusalem's wickedness exceeds the pagans'. The nations surrounding Jerusalem did not have the law; Jerusalem had it and defied it. This is the logic of Rom 2:17-24 (the Jew who has the law and breaks it dishonors God more than the Gentile who does not have it) and Jesus's woes on Chorazin and Bethsaida (Matt 11:21-22: worse than Tyre and Sidon in judgment because they had more light).</p>",
  "7": "<p>'Because you have exceeded (<strong>hamonem</strong>, <em>hamōnĕkem</em>) the nations around you in rebellion — you have not followed my statutes, kept my ordinances, or even lived up to the standards of the nations surrounding you.' The triple failure: statutes, ordinances, even pagan ethical standards. The final point is most stinging: Israel has not even maintained the moral standards of pagans. The nations have natural law (Rom 2:14-15); Israel has natural law plus revealed law, and has violated both. <em>Ḥuqqôt</em> (statutes) and <em>mišpāṭîm</em> (ordinances) are the two primary covenant-law categories of Deuteronomy.</p>",
  "8": "<p>'I — yes, I myself (<strong>ani ani</strong>, <em>ʾănî ʾănî</em>) — am against you' (<strong>hineni eleich</strong>, <em>hinnĕnî ʾēlayik</em>). The divine first-person double emphasis intensifies the direct confrontation: no intermediary, no proxy, YHWH himself is the adversary. This is the opposite of the covenant formula 'I will be your God' — when the covenant partner becomes the covenant-breaker, the God who was with them becomes the God who is against them. 'I will execute my judgments in your midst in the sight of the nations' — the public judgment that reverses the public blessing.</p>",
  "9": "<p>'I will do to you what I have never done before and will never do again, on account of all your abominations.' The singularity of Jerusalem's judgment: unprecedented and unrepeatable. The hyperbole of singularity (also in Joel 2:2 and Matt 24:21 for the final tribulation) marks the watershed quality of the 586 BCE destruction. The claim that this has never been done before and will not be done again is not an absolute chronological assertion but a judgment of qualitative intensity — the closest analog in Israel's experience to the eschatological judgment.</p>",
  "10": "<p>'Fathers will eat their sons within you, and sons will eat their fathers.' The covenant curse of cannibalism — the ultimate covenant curse of Lev 26:29 and Deut 28:53-57 (eating your own children in the siege). The physical act of siege-driven cannibalism is both the literal historical reality of siege warfare (Lamentations 4:10 records it happening in 586 BCE) and the covenant-curse vocabulary of Deuteronomy come to literal fulfillment. The survivors will be scattered to every wind — exile as the second stage of judgment after the internal destruction.</p>",
  "11": "<p><strong>hay ani</strong> (<em>ḥay ʾānî</em>): 'as I live' — the divine oath formula using YHWH's own life as the guarantee. This is one of the most solemn forms of divine speech in the OT; it appears 16 times in Ezekiel (more than any other book). The divine oath that requires no external witness — YHWH swears by himself because there is no greater thing to swear by (Heb 6:13: since God had no one greater to swear by, he swore by himself). <strong>gara</strong> (<em>gāraʿ</em>): 'cut down/diminish' — 'my eye will not spare' (<em>lōʾ tāḥûs ʿênî</em>): the idiom for divine implacability (cf. 7:4, 9; 8:18; 9:5, 10).</p>",
  "12": "<p>The tripartite judgment statement in its fullest form: a third will die by plague and famine within you; a third will fall by the sword outside you; a third I will scatter to every wind, drawing a sword in pursuit. The comprehensive exhaustion of judgment: no exit left. The interior (plague/famine), the exterior (sword), and the diaspora (scatter) — the three spatial domains of the city (inside walls, outside walls, dispersed) — are all subject to divine judgment. No geographic location provides immunity.</p>",
  "13": "<p>'Then my anger will be exhausted (<strong>yikhleh api</strong>, <em>yikleh ʾappî</em>), my fury will rest upon them (<strong>vahanachot chamati</strong>, <em>wahanōḥōt ḥămātî</em>) and find its end.' The divine anger has an end — it is not infinite or capricious but measured and teleological. <em>Kālâ</em> (to be completed, exhausted) indicates that the anger has a finite quantity matched to the sin. After the anger is spent, something new is possible. This restraint within divine judgment — even in the most severe oracle — preserves the possibility of the restoration that Ezekiel will prophesy in chapters 33-37.</p>",
  "14": "<p>'I will make you a ruin and a disgrace (<strong>cherpah</strong>, <em>ḥerpâ</em>) among the surrounding nations, in the sight of all who pass by.' <em>Ḥerpâh</em> (reproach, disgrace) — the covenant curse of public shame before the nations (Deut 28:37). Jerusalem as a curse and a byword among the nations is the inversion of its calling to be a blessing (Gen 12:3). The public nature of the judgment ('in the sight of all who pass by') mirrors the public nature of Jerusalem's privilege: the city placed at the center of the nations falls publicly before the nations.</p>",
  "15": "<p>'You will be a disgrace and a mockery (<strong>kelimah ugeduphah</strong>), a warning and a horror, to the surrounding nations.' The four terms for shame — disgrace, mockery, warning (<strong>musar</strong>, <em>mûsār</em>, also 'correction/discipline'), horror (<strong>shamamah</strong>, <em>šammâ</em>) — describe the reaction of the nations to Jerusalem's fall. The same terms will reverse when God restores Israel before the nations (36:30: no longer bring disgrace). The shame vocabulary is not merely descriptive but judicial: these are the formal covenantal penalties named in Deut 28:37 and Jer 24:9.</p>",
  "16": "<p>The deadly arrows of famine (<strong>chitsim hara'im hare'av</strong>, <em>ḥiṣṣîm hārāʿîm hārāʿāb</em>): 'the evil arrows of hunger/famine.' YHWH as archer, launching famine as arrows. The image of divine judgment as archery appears in Ps 38:2 (divine arrows sunk into the psalmist), Lam 3:12-13 (YHWH bent his bow and made the psalmist the target). The arrows aimed for destruction — <strong>lemashchit</strong> (<em>lĕmašḥît</em>): for destruction, for the Destroyer (the same root as the destroyer of the Passover, Exod 12:23).</p>",
  "17": "<p>The full catalog of judgment instruments: famine (<strong>raav</strong>), ferocious beasts (<strong>chayyah raah</strong>, <em>ḥayyâ rāʿâ</em>), childlessness from bereavement (<strong>shikhel</strong>, <em>šiḵḵēl</em>), pestilence (<strong>dever</strong>), bloodshed (<strong>dam</strong>), and the sword (<strong>charev</strong>). This is the complete covenant-curse arsenal of Leviticus 26: wild animals (26:22), pestilence (26:25), sword (26:25, 33), famine (26:26). All the covenant curses enumerated in Lev 26 are being sent upon Jerusalem simultaneously. 'I the LORD have spoken' (<em>ʾănî Yhwh dibbartî</em>) — the formula that seals the oracle and identifies its source as YHWH's own word."
}

